sh}}\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/11th/armiehammer|title=Armie Hammer - The Shorty Awards|website=shortyawards.com|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Broadway.com Audience Awards]]\n|Favorite Breakthrough Performance (Male)\n|''[[Straight White Men]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/195749/fan-picked-2019-broadwaycom-audience-choice-award-nominations-announced-be-more-chill-leads-with-12/|title=Fan-Picked 2019 Broadway.com Audience Choice Award Nominations Announced; Be More Chill Leads With 12|website=Broadway.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|2309517}}\n* {{Amg name|484612}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hammer, Armie}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Highland Park, Texas]]\n", "name_user": "Izzyiscool", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armie_Hammer"}
{"title_page": "Michael Park (actor)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Michael Park\n| image         = Michael Park.jpg\n| caption       = Park in 2010\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name    = Michael Frank Park\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1968|07|20}}\n| birth_place   = [[Canandaigua (city), New York|Canandaigua, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| alma_mater    = [[Nazareth College (New York)|Nazareth College]]\n| occupation    = Actor\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Laurie Nowak|1996}}\n| children      = 3\n}}\n\n'''Michael Frank Park''' (born July 20, 1968) is an American actor, best known for his role as Jack Snyder on ''[[As the World Turns]]'' (1997\u2013 2010). Park won back-to-back Daytime Emmy Awards for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series in 2010 and 2011.\n\nOn stage, he has originated roles in three [[Broadway musicals]]: Michael in ''[[Smokey Joe's Cafe]]'' (1995), Angus Tuck in ''[[Tuck Everlasting (musical)|Tuck Everlasting]]'' (2016), and Larry Murphy in ''[[Dear Evan Hansen]]'' (2016), as well as Monty in the [[Off-Broadway]] production of ''Violet'' (1997).\n\nIn 2018, for his work in ''Dear Evan Hansen'', Park earned a [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album]] and a [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Musical Performance in a Daytime Program]].\n\nIn 2019, Park played snooty reporter, Tom Holloway, in the third season of Netflix\u2019s critically acclaimed ''[[Stranger Things]]''.\n\n==Career==\nPark attended [[Nazareth College (New York)|Nazareth College]], [[Rochester, New York]], originally intending to become an architect, before deciding to become an actor.<ref>[http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/michael-park/bio/258233 \"Michael Park Biography\"] tvguide.com, accessed June 26, 2011</ref> He worked in the 1992 New Plays Festival at Geva Theatre in Rochester. He appeared in regional productions including ''Ellen Universe Joins The Band'' and ''Peephole''.<ref>[http://michaelparkonline.net/Bio.htm Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114015512/http://michaelparkonline.net/Bio.htm |date=2012-01-14 }} michaelparkonline.net, accessed June 26, 2011</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Park appeared in the musical ''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]'' at [[Lincoln Center Theater]].<ref>Richards, David.[http://michaelparkonline.net/HelloAgain.htm \"Review of 'Helo Again'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110729051524/http://michaelparkonline.net/HelloAgain.htm |date=2011-07-29 }} ''New York Times'' (from michaelparkonline.net), January 31, 1994</ref> In August 1994, Park was in the [[Goodspeed Opera House]] production of ''[[Shenandoah (musical)|Shenandoah]]'',<ref>Richards, David.[https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/18/theater/theater-review-shenandoah-in-a-20th-anniversary-go-round.html?scp=1&sq=%22Goodspeed+Opera+House%22&st=nyt THEATER REVIEW; 'Shenandoah' in a 20th-Anniversary Go-Round\"] ''New York Times'', August 18, 1994</ref> and ''[[Good News (musical)|Good News]]'' at the [[North Shore Music Theatre]] (1994). After understudying Billy Bigelow in the 1994 revival of Rodgers and Hammerstein's ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'', he made his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut in 1995 in ''[[Smokey Joe's Cafe]]''.<ref>Brantley, Ben.[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/03/03/theater/theater-review-smokey-joe-s-cafe-the-song-s-the-thing-a-leiber-stoller-revue.html?scp=1&sq=&pagewanted=1 \"Theater Review: 'Smokey Joe's Cafe'\"] ''New York Times'', March 3, 1995</ref> In 1997, Park played Monty in the [[Playwrights Horizons]] production of ''[[Violet (musical)|Violet]]''.<ref>Heineman, Eva.[http://www.curtainup.com/violet.html \"A CurtainUp Review:'Violet'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080105064122/http://www.curtainup.com/violet.html |date=2008-01-05 }} ''CurtainUp'', accessed June 26, 2011</ref>\n\nThe day after ''Violet'' opened was Park's first day in the long-running daytime [[soap opera]] ''As the World Turns'' as Jack Snyder, joining in April 1997.<ref>[http://www.soap-news.com/atwt/a/park.htm \"Michael Park\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928150825/http://www.soap-news.com/atwt/a/park.htm |date=2011-09-28 }} soap-news.com, accessed June 26, 2011</ref> Park received three Emmy nominations and several other soap-opera acting awards, including winning the 2010 and 2011 [[Daytime Emmy Award]]s for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series.<ref>Gioia, Michael.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/151979-How-to-Succeeds-Michael-Park-Among-Winners-at-38th-Annual-Daytime-Emmy-Awards How to Succeed's Michael Park Among Winners at 38th Annual Daytime Emmy Awards\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625001922/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/151979-How-to-Succeeds-Michael-Park-Among-Winners-at-38th-Annual-Daytime-Emmy-Awards |date=2011-06-25 }} playbill.com, June 20, 2011</ref>\n\nDuring his 13-year tenure in ''As the World Turns'', he continued to work in the theatre, playing Lucky Malone in the [[Roundabout Theatre Company]]'s revival of ''[[Little Me (musical)|Little Me]]'' (1998).<ref>McGrath, Sean et al.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/41965-Roundabouts-Little-Me-Hopes-For-Big-Laughs-From-Prince-Short-Opens-Nov-12 \"Roundabout's 'Little Me' Hopes For Big Laughs From Prince & Short; Opens Nov. 12\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021142601/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/41965-Roundabouts-Little-Me-Hopes-For-Big-Laughs-From-Prince-Short-Opens-Nov-12 |date=2012-10-21 }} November 12, 1998</ref> He made two New York City Center [[Encores!]] appearances: ''[[Bloomer Girl]]'' in 2001 as Jeff Calhoun, and ''[[Applause (musical)|Applause]]'' in 2008 as Bill Sampson.<ref>Fox, Jena Tesse.[http://www.broadwayworld.com/viewcolumn.cfm?colid=24963 \"Applause and Encores for Michael Park\"] broadwayworld.com, February 7, 2008</ref>\n\nWith ''As the World Turns'' coming to an end in June 2010, Park returned to the stage, and played the role of Pete's ghost father who appeared to his son as three \"Alamo\" characters in the coming-of-age musical ''The Burnt Part Boys'' at Playwrights Horizon.<ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/139154-Burnt-Part-Boys-a-Musical-Tale-of-West-Virginia-Begins-in-NYC-Park-Brady-Calderon-Star \"'Burnt Part Boys', a Musical Tale of West Virginia, Begins in NYC; Park, Brady, Calderon Star\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719145455/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/139154-Burnt-Part-Boys-a-Musical-Tale-of-West-Virginia-Begins-in-NYC-Park-Brady-Calderon-Star |date=2010-07-19 }} playbill.com, April 30, 2010</ref> In the summer of 2010, he appeared as Lord Capulet in the musical ''The Last Goodbye'' at [[Williamstown Theatre Festival]].<ref>Rizzo, Frank.[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?hl=en&lr=&q=cache:M3VqEApiVt4J:http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117943341?refCatId=33+%22The+Last+Goodbye%22+%22Michael+Park%22+Williamstown&ct=clnk \"Legit Reviews: 'The Last Goodbye'\"] ''Variety'', August 15, 2010</ref> Park then appeared as the cop in [[Will Eno]]'s play ''Middletown'' at the off-Broadway [[Vineyard Theatre]] (2010).<ref>Probst, Andy.[http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/reviews/11-2010/middletown_31503.html \"Review: 'Middletown'\"] theatermania.com, November 4, 2010</ref>\n\nPark performed in the role of Bert Bratt in the Broadway revival ''[[How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying]]'' (2011), starring [[Daniel Radcliffe]] and [[John Larroquette]].<ref>Hetrick, Adam. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/149202-That-Grin-of-Impetuous-Youth-How-to-Succeed-Revival-With-Daniel-Radcliffe-Opens-on-Broadway \"That Grin of Impetuous Youth\": 'How to Succeed' Revival, With Daniel Radcliffe, Opens on Broadway\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601123632/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/149202-That-Grin-of-Impetuous-Youth-How-to-Succeed-Revival-With-Daniel-Radcliffe-Opens-on-Broadway |date=2011-06-01 }} playbill.com, March 27, 2011</ref>\n\nIn the 2012 independent financial thriller film ''[[Supercapitalist]]'', Park appears as Morris Brown, co-starring along with [[Linus Roache]], [[Kenneth Tsang]], Derek Ting, [[Richard Ng]], [[Kathy Uyen]], and Darren E. Scott.\n\nOn December 5, 2013, he participated as a cast member of the [[NBC]] telecast production of ''[[The Sound of Music Live!]]'' starring [[Carrie Underwood]]. He played Cecco, one of Captain Hook's pirates, in the NBC presentation of ''[[Peter Pan Live!]]'' starring [[Allison Williams (actress)|Allison Williams]] and [[Christopher Walken]]; the musical was broadcast on December 4, 2014.<ref>Hetrick, Adam. [http://playbill.com/news/article/handful-of-broadway-newsies-make-up-peter-pans-lost-boys-and-swashbuckling-pirates-332444# \"Handful of Broadway Newsies Make Up Peter Pan's Lost Boys and Swashbuckling Pirates\"], Playbill, October 7, 2014</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he created the role of Larry Murphy in the world premiere of the stage musical ''[[Dear Evan Hansen]]'' at Washington, DC's [[Arena Stage]]. The musical opened off-Broadway at the [[Second Stage Theater]] in the Spring of 2016, though he was not in the cast as he was appearing in the Broadway musical, ''[[Tuck Everlasting (musical)|Tuck Everlasting]]''.<ref>[https://www.ibdb.com/Production/View/501949 Tuck Everlasting] [[The Broadway League]]. 2016. Retrieved March 8, 2016</ref> He returned to ''Dear Evan Hansen'' in the Fall of 2016 when the musical made its debut on Broadway. For his work in ''Dear Evan Hansen'', Michael Park earned the 2018 [[Grammy Award]] for Best Musical Theater Album and his third [[Daytime Emmy Award]], this one a Daytime Creative Arts Emmy Award for Outstanding Musical Performance in a Daytime Program for his and the rest of the cast's ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'' performance that was broadcast on April 25, 2017.<ref>McPhee, Ryan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/dear-evan-hansen-wins-2018-grammy-award-for-best-musical-theater-album# \"Dear Evan Hansen Wins 2018 Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album\"], Playbill, January 28, 2018</ref><ref>McPhee, Ryan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/ben-platt-and-dear-evan-hansen-co-stars-win-daytime-creative-arts-emmy-award# \"Ben Platt and Dear Evan Hansen Co-Stars Win Daytime Creative Arts Emmy Award\"], Playbill, April 28, 2018</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPark was born in [[Canandaigua (city), New York|Canandaigua, New York]], but spent a year of his childhood in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rf6CntBr_pg|title=KDKA: ATWT in Pittsburgh (Michael Park, Maura West, Paul Leyden)|author=MichaelParkNet|date=November 2, 2009|publisher=KDKA|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nHe has been married to music therapist Laurie Nowak since January 6, 1996. They have three children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soapcentral.com/atwt/theactors/park_michael.php|title=About the Actors \u2013 Michael Park|website=soapcentral.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jack Snyder and Carly Tenney]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0661906|name=Michael Park}}\n*{{IBDB name|55523}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050308021627/http://www.soapcentral.com/atwt/theactors/park.php SoapCentral entry]\n\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Lead Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Park, Michael}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series winners]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]] <!-- https://twitter.com/park24hrs/status/1100370700890791941 -->\n[[Category:Male actors from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Nazareth College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Canandaigua, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Michael Park\n| image         = [[File:Michael Park.jpg|thumb|Michael Park 2010]]\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name    = Michael Frank Park\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1968|07|20}}\n| birth_place   = [[Canandaigua (city), New York|Canandaigua, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| alma_mater    = [[Nazareth College (New York)|Nazareth College]]\n| occupation    = Actor\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Laurie Nowak|1996}}\n| children      = 3\n}}\n\n'''Michael Frank Park''' (born July 20, 1968) is an American actor, best known for his role as Jack Snyder on ''[[As the World Turns]]'' (1997\u2013 2010). Park won back-to-back Daytime Emmy Awards for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series in 2010 and 2011. \n\nOn stage, he has originated roles in three [[Broadway musicals]]: Michael in ''[[Smokey Joe's Cafe]]'' (1995), Angus Tuck in ''[[Tuck Everlasting (musical)|Tuck Everlasting]]'' (2016), and Larry Murphy in ''[[Dear Evan Hansen]]'' (2016), as well as Monty in the [[Off-Broadway]] production of ''Violet'' (1997). \n\nIn 2018, for his work in ''Dear Evan Hansen'', Park earned a [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album]] and a [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Musical Performance in a Daytime Program]].\n\nIn 2019, Park played snooty reporter, Tom Holloway, in the third season of Netflix\u2019s critically acclaimed ''[[Stranger Things]]''.\n\n==Career==\nPark attended [[Nazareth College (New York)|Nazareth College]], [[Rochester, New York]], originally intending to become an architect, before deciding to become an actor.<ref>[http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/michael-park/bio/258233 \"Michael Park Biography\"] tvguide.com, accessed June 26, 2011</ref> He worked in the 1992 New Plays Festival at Geva Theatre in Rochester. He appeared in regional productions including ''Ellen Universe Joins The Band'' and ''Peephole''.<ref>[http://michaelparkonline.net/Bio.htm Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114015512/http://michaelparkonline.net/Bio.htm |date=2012-01-14 }} michaelparkonline.net, accessed June 26, 2011</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Park appeared in the musical ''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]'' at [[Lincoln Center Theater]].<ref>Richards, David.[http://michaelparkonline.net/HelloAgain.htm \"Review of 'Helo Again'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110729051524/http://michaelparkonline.net/HelloAgain.htm |date=2011-07-29 }} ''New York Times'' (from michaelparkonline.net), January 31, 1994</ref> In August 1994, Park was in the [[Goodspeed Opera House]] production of ''[[Shenandoah (musical)|Shenandoah]]'',<ref>Richards, David.[https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/18/theater/theater-review-shenandoah-in-a-20th-anniversary-go-round.html?scp=1&sq=%22Goodspeed+Opera+House%22&st=nyt THEATER REVIEW; 'Shenandoah' in a 20th-Anniversary Go-Round\"] ''New York Times'', August 18, 1994</ref> and ''[[Good News (musical)|Good News]]'' at the [[North Shore Music Theatre]] (1994). After understudying Billy Bigelow in the 1994 revival of Rodgers and Hammerstein's ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'', he made his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut in 1995 in ''[[Smokey Joe's Cafe]]''.<ref>Brantley, Ben.[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/03/03/theater/theater-review-smokey-joe-s-cafe-the-song-s-the-thing-a-leiber-stoller-revue.html?scp=1&sq=&pagewanted=1 \"Theater Review: 'Smokey Joe's Cafe'\"] ''New York Times'', March 3, 1995</ref> In 1997, Park played Monty in the [[Playwrights Horizons]] production of ''[[Violet (musical)|Violet]]''.<ref>Heineman, Eva.[http://www.curtainup.com/violet.html \"A CurtainUp Review:'Violet'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080105064122/http://www.curtainup.com/violet.html |date=2008-01-05 }} ''CurtainUp'', accessed June 26, 2011</ref>\n\nThe day after ''Violet'' opened was Park's first day in the long-running daytime [[soap opera]] ''As the World Turns'' as Jack Snyder, joining in April 1997.<ref>[http://www.soap-news.com/atwt/a/park.htm \"Michael Park\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928150825/http://www.soap-news.com/atwt/a/park.htm |date=2011-09-28 }} soap-news.com, accessed June 26, 2011</ref> Park received three Emmy nominations and several other soap-opera acting awards, including winning the 2010 and 2011 [[Daytime Emmy Award]]s for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series.<ref>Gioia, Michael.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/151979-How-to-Succeeds-Michael-Park-Among-Winners-at-38th-Annual-Daytime-Emmy-Awards How to Succeed's Michael Park Among Winners at 38th Annual Daytime Emmy Awards\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625001922/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/151979-How-to-Succeeds-Michael-Park-Among-Winners-at-38th-Annual-Daytime-Emmy-Awards |date=2011-06-25 }} playbill.com, June 20, 2011</ref>\n\nDuring his 13-year tenure in ''As the World Turns'', he continued to work in the theatre, playing Lucky Malone in the [[Roundabout Theatre Company]]'s revival of ''[[Little Me (musical)|Little Me]]'' (1998).<ref>McGrath, Sean et al.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/41965-Roundabouts-Little-Me-Hopes-For-Big-Laughs-From-Prince-Short-Opens-Nov-12 \"Roundabout's 'Little Me' Hopes For Big Laughs From Prince & Short; Opens Nov. 12\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021142601/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/41965-Roundabouts-Little-Me-Hopes-For-Big-Laughs-From-Prince-Short-Opens-Nov-12 |date=2012-10-21 }} November 12, 1998</ref> He made two New York City Center [[Encores!]] appearances: ''[[Bloomer Girl]]'' in 2001 as Jeff Calhoun, and ''[[Applause (musical)|Applause]]'' in 2008 as Bill Sampson.<ref>Fox, Jena Tesse.[http://www.broadwayworld.com/viewcolumn.cfm?colid=24963 \"Applause and Encores for Michael Park\"] broadwayworld.com, February 7, 2008</ref>\n\nWith ''As the World Turns'' coming to an end in June 2010, Park returned to the stage, and played the role of Pete's ghost father who appeared to his son as three \"Alamo\" characters in the coming-of-age musical ''The Burnt Part Boys'' at Playwrights Horizon.<ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/139154-Burnt-Part-Boys-a-Musical-Tale-of-West-Virginia-Begins-in-NYC-Park-Brady-Calderon-Star \"'Burnt Part Boys', a Musical Tale of West Virginia, Begins in NYC; Park, Brady, Calderon Star\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719145455/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/139154-Burnt-Part-Boys-a-Musical-Tale-of-West-Virginia-Begins-in-NYC-Park-Brady-Calderon-Star |date=2010-07-19 }} playbill.com, April 30, 2010</ref> In the summer of 2010, he appeared as Lord Capulet in the musical ''The Last Goodbye'' at [[Williamstown Theatre Festival]].<ref>Rizzo, Frank.[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?hl=en&lr=&q=cache:M3VqEApiVt4J:http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117943341?refCatId=33+%22The+Last+Goodbye%22+%22Michael+Park%22+Williamstown&ct=clnk \"Legit Reviews: 'The Last Goodbye'\"] ''Variety'', August 15, 2010</ref> Park then appeared as the cop in [[Will Eno]]'s play ''Middletown'' at the off-Broadway [[Vineyard Theatre]] (2010).<ref>Probst, Andy.[http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/reviews/11-2010/middletown_31503.html \"Review: 'Middletown'\"] theatermania.com, November 4, 2010</ref>\n\nPark performed in the role of Bert Bratt in the Broadway revival ''[[How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying]]'' (2011), starring [[Daniel Radcliffe]] and [[John Larroquette]].<ref>Hetrick, Adam. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/149202-That-Grin-of-Impetuous-Youth-How-to-Succeed-Revival-With-Daniel-Radcliffe-Opens-on-Broadway \"That Grin of Impetuous Youth\": 'How to Succeed' Revival, With Daniel Radcliffe, Opens on Broadway\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601123632/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/149202-That-Grin-of-Impetuous-Youth-How-to-Succeed-Revival-With-Daniel-Radcliffe-Opens-on-Broadway |date=2011-06-01 }} playbill.com, March 27, 2011</ref>\n\nIn the 2012 independent financial thriller film ''[[Supercapitalist]]'', Park appears as Morris Brown, co-starring along with [[Linus Roache]], [[Kenneth Tsang]], Derek Ting, [[Richard Ng]], [[Kathy Uyen]], and Darren E. Scott.\n\nOn December 5, 2013, he participated as a cast member of the [[NBC]] telecast production of ''[[The Sound of Music Live!]]'' starring [[Carrie Underwood]]. He played Cecco, one of Captain Hook's pirates, in the NBC presentation of ''[[Peter Pan Live!]]'' starring [[Allison Williams (actress)|Allison Williams]] and [[Christopher Walken]]; the musical was broadcast on December 4, 2014.<ref>Hetrick, Adam. [http://playbill.com/news/article/handful-of-broadway-newsies-make-up-peter-pans-lost-boys-and-swashbuckling-pirates-332444# \"Handful of Broadway Newsies Make Up Peter Pan's Lost Boys and Swashbuckling Pirates\"], Playbill, October 7, 2014</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he created the role of Larry Murphy in the world premiere of the stage musical ''[[Dear Evan Hansen]]'' at Washington, DC's [[Arena Stage]]. The musical opened off-Broadway at the [[Second Stage Theater]] in the Spring of 2016, though he was not in the cast as he was appearing in the Broadway musical, ''[[Tuck Everlasting (musical)| Tuck Everlasting]]''.<ref>[https://www.ibdb.com/Production/View/501949 Tuck Everlasting] [[The Broadway League]]. 2016. Retrieved March 8, 2016</ref> He returned to ''Dear Evan Hansen'' in the Fall of 2016 when the musical made its debut on Broadway. For his work in ''Dear Evan Hansen'', Michael Park earned the 2018 [[Grammy Award]] for Best Musical Theater Album and his third [[Daytime Emmy Award]], this one a Daytime Creative Arts Emmy Award for Outstanding Musical Performance in a Daytime Program for his and the rest of the cast's ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'' performance that was broadcast on April 25, 2017.<ref>McPhee, Ryan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/dear-evan-hansen-wins-2018-grammy-award-for-best-musical-theater-album# \"Dear Evan Hansen Wins 2018 Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album\"], Playbill, January 28, 2018</ref><ref>McPhee, Ryan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/ben-platt-and-dear-evan-hansen-co-stars-win-daytime-creative-arts-emmy-award# \"Ben Platt and Dear Evan Hansen Co-Stars Win Daytime Creative Arts Emmy Award\"], Playbill, April 28, 2018</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPark was born in [[Canandaigua (city), New York|Canandaigua, New York]], but spent a year of his childhood in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rf6CntBr_pg|title=KDKA: ATWT in Pittsburgh (Michael Park, Maura West, Paul Leyden)|author=MichaelParkNet|date=November 2, 2009|publisher=KDKA|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nHe has been married to music therapist Laurie Nowak since January 6, 1996. They have three children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soapcentral.com/atwt/theactors/park_michael.php|title=About the Actors \u2013 Michael Park|website=soapcentral.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jack Snyder and Carly Tenney]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0661906|name=Michael Park}}\n*{{IBDB name|55523}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050308021627/http://www.soapcentral.com/atwt/theactors/park.php SoapCentral entry]\n\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Lead Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Park, Michael}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series winners]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]] <!-- https://twitter.com/park24hrs/status/1100370700890791941 -->\n[[Category:Male actors from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Nazareth College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Canandaigua, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Shanze1", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, fixing infobox with  thumbnail image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Park_(actor)"}
